\section{Introduction}
\begin{spacing}{1}
\fontsize{18}{21}\selectfont
I chose SCLY3 (ENSG00000000457.14) as main Gene and DPM1 (ENSG00000000419.13) as secondary Gene for my final project. SCLY3-medicated ROCK2 protein stability may play a role in the growth and metastasis of HCC cells(NIH, 2022). Moreover, disease associated with SCYL3 include Afferent Loop Syndrome and Facial Neuralgia (GeneCards). 
Mutation of DPM1 is associated with congenital disorder of glycosylation type 1e (Proteinatlas org). Glycosylation type 1e rare disorder of multiple glycosylation pathways characterized by global developmental delay, motor skills delay, hypotonia, seizures, microcephaly and eye abnormalities (including retinopathy, nystagmus, strabismus) with varying onset and severity (NIH). Additional clinical features may include peripheral neuropathy, dysmorphic features (facial and limb abnormalities), ataxia and severe gastrointestinal involvement (NIH). 

I chose SCLY3 with the interest to explore pathogen of the disease by analyzing Definition) and predisposition by analyzing Vital status) and DPM1 to find any relationship between SCLY3 in neurological disease perspective. 
\end{spacing}

\section{Methods}
\fontsize{18}{21}\selectfont
\subsection{Summary Statistics}
I used Readr, Knitr and Dplyr. Readr provides provides a fast and user-friendly way to read rectangular data from delimited files, such as comma-separated values (CSV) and tab-seperated values (TSV). Knitr function is to generate markdown tables without heavy code work. Dplyr its ability to manipulate date in an easy, readable way and apply summary functions to columns to create a new table of summary statistics. 

\subsection{Histogram and Scatter Plot}
For histogram, I used ggplot2, gridExtra and tibble packages. 
The ggplot2 packages allows to quickly plot attractive graphics and to visualize and explore data. The gridExtra is useful functions for combining plots. 
The tibble packages provides utilities for handling tibbles, where “tibble” is a colloquial term for the S3 tbl_df class. Tibble is the central data structure for the set of packages known as the tidyverse, including dplyr, ggplot2, tidyr and readr. 

\subsection{Violin Plot}
For violin plot, I used ggplot2, gridExtra, tibble and dplyr packages that have been discussed in histogram and scatter plot. I would like to talk pipe-function ($<$). Pipe function works essentially in this plot as I was trying to join counts with the meta data frame, matching them on the column .sample. Dplyr works well with pipe function ($>$), which basically feeds output into new functions

\subsection{Heatmap}
For Heatmap, I used Complex Heatmap, Circlize and grid packages. 
Complex Heatmaps are efficient to visualize association between different sources of data sets and reveal potential patterns. Complex Heatmap package provides a highly flexible way to arrange multiple heatmaps and supports various annotation graphics (Bioconductor). 
Circlize is a package is to provide circular visualization. Circular layout is an efficient way for visualization of huge amounts of information (CRAN). 
Grid package provides primitive graphical functions that underlie the ggplot2 plotting system. Grid is low-level, typically used to modify very specific elements of a plot, rather than being functions to use for one-line plotting call while ggplot2 function allows to change the theme of a plot (including specific elements of the theme for plot), to customize the colors used within the plot, and to create faceted “small multiple” graphs (Bookdown). 

\subsection{Jitter Plot}
Packages used were ggplot2, dplyr and ggpubr. The ggplot2 and dplyr have been discussed earlier. The package in R provides a convenient interface for creating publication-ready plots by extending the functionality of ggplot2. It offers additional themes, geoms, and tools for combining multiple plots, adding annotations, and creating complex figures suitable for research and presentation (Geeksforgeeks).

